<F P=100> ISRAEL </F>
<H3> <TI>   Restrictions on Aviation Described </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Restrictions on Aviation Described </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   TA0805150394 Jerusalem Qol Yisra'el in Hebrew 1200 GMT 8 May 
94 </F>

<F P=103> TA0805150394 </F>
<F P=104>  Jerusalem Qol Yisra'el </F>
<F P=105>  Hebrew </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Transportation Minister Yisra'el Qeysar has stated 
that no arms will be allowed aboard the six planes to be used by 
the Palestinians in the Gaza Strip and Jericho. The head of the 
Civil Aviation Administration made it clear that the security 
arrangements in the two airstrips in Gaza and Jericho will be 
similar to security arrangements in the Rafah and Allenby Bridge 
border terminals. The Palestinians will be allowed to use two 
helicopters and four light planes, including Yasir 'Arafat's 
plane, which will serve him in his flights between Gaza and 
Jericho. All the Palestinian aerial activity will be conducted 
under the supervision of the Israel Civil Aviation 
Administration, and the pilots will have to undergo a special 
test by this body. 
  Minister Qeysar, who toured the Jordan Valley settlements 
and 
the Bet She'an Valley region today, also said that the 
construction of the Jericho bypass road will cost approximately 
200 million shekels. Minister Qeysar added that his office has 
already prepared detailed plans and maps toward the resumption 
of the land and sea link between Israel and Jordan after a peace 
agreement is signed between the two countries. He noted that 
Israel is interested in supplying Jordan with transport and 
commerce services via the ports of Haifa and Ashdod. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

