<F P=100> ISRAEL </F>
<H3> <TI>   Rothschild on Difficulties of Self-Rule </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Rothschild on Difficulties of Self-Rule </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   TA0705105494 Jerusalem Qol Yisra'el in Hebrew 0800 GMT 7 May 
94 </F>

<F P=103> TA0705105494 </F>
<F P=104>  Jerusalem Qol Yisra'el </F>
<F P=105>  Hebrew </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Major General Dani Rothschild, coordinator of 
government activities in the territories, believes the power 
struggle between the local leaders in the territories and the 
PLO-Tunis leadership will continue. In his opinion, the PLO 
will find operating the self-rule difficult unless it assigns 
the local leaders a greater role. The local leaders, he says, 
will continue supporting the peace process in any event and will 
not join the anti-'Arafat organizations. 
  Speaking to our correspondent, Gen. Rothschild said the 
Palestinians began by demanding that Israel leave them to manage 
their affairs on their own, but they soon realized that the task 
was very complex. 
  The true test of the agreement's implementation, in the 
coordinator's opinion, will be the extent of the population's 
satisfaction and the rate of improvement in every sphere of 
life. Unless such improvement is attained, the strength of Hamas 
[Islamic Resistance Movement] and the other opposition forces 
will rise. 
  As for the next phase of the Cairo agreements, Gen. 
Rothschild does not anticipate easy negotiations on the early 
Palestinian empowerment in the rest of Judaea and Samaria. The 
matter is complicated, because we will be discussing joint 
Israeli-Palestinian bodies, he said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

