<F P=100> ISRAEL </F>
<H3> <TI>   Sources: Shuttle No Substitute for Direct Talks </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Sources: Shuttle No Substitute for Direct Talks </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   TA1005091494 Tel Aviv HA'ARETZ in Hebrew 10 May 94 p A5 </F>
<F P=103> TA1005091494 </F>
<F P=104>  Tel Aviv HA'ARETZ </F>
<F P=105>  Hebrew </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by political correspondent Aluf Ben and Washington </F>
correspondent 'Aqiva Eldar] 
  [Excerpts] Israel does not view U.S. Secretary of State 
Warren Christopher's shuttle mission as a substitute for direct 
talks with Syria, either in the framework of the Washington 
talks or at a higher level, senior political sources stated 
yesterday. According to these sources, Israel regards the U.S. 
mediation as an auxiliary element of the negotiations aimed at 
settling matters of principle, but believes the details must be 
discussed directly by the sides. [passage omitted] 
  The senior political sources said that the gap between the 
Israeli and Syrian positions is very big and that detailed 
deliberations in working groups can only start after a framework 
for the negotiations has been determined. [passage omitted] 
  'Aqiva Eldar reports: The United States neither supports nor 
rejects the Israeli plan for an arrangement with Syria. Israeli 
and U.S. officials in Washington asserted yesterday that 
Secretary Christopher relayed the Israeli proposal to Syrian 
President Hafiz al-Asad without adopting a position on it. 
Referring to the banner headline in HA'ARETZ yesterday ("The 
United States Has Reservations About the Israeli Proposal"), 
Israeli sources said they had been told by senior State 
Department officials that Christopher had neither rejected nor 
criticized the Israeli proposals. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

