<F P=100> ISRAEL </F>
<H3> <TI>   Decision Passed Not To Abrogate Golan Law </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Decision Passed Not To Abrogate Golan Law </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   TA1005045094 Jerusalem Qol Yisra'el in Hebrew 0400 GMT 10 
May 94 </F>

<F P=103> TA1005045094 </F>
<F P=104>  Jerusalem Qol Yisra'el </F>
<F P=105>  Hebrew </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] In deliberations conducted by the Prime Minister's 
Office and the Foreign Ministry, it was decided not to abrogate 
the Golan Law because it relates to the residents of the area 
and not to the territory itself and because internal political 
problems will make its abrogation difficult. 
  Our political correspondent Shlomo Raz reports that U.S. 
Secretary of State Warren Christopher is due to return to the 
region next week to resume the negotiations between Israel and 
Syria. 

</TEXT>

