<F P=100> ISRAEL </F>
<H3> <TI>   Peres Denies Talks on Unresolved Issues To Stop </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Peres Denies Talks on Unresolved Issues To Stop </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   TA1005103694 Tel Aviv 'AL HAMISHMAR in Hebrew 10 May 94 p 4 </F>
<F P=103> TA1005103694 </F>
<F P=104>  Tel Aviv 'AL HAMISHMAR </F>
<F P=105>  Hebrew </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Rami Shani] </F>
  [Text] Foreign Minister Shim'on Peres yesterday reiterated 
the government's commitment to safeguarding the security of the 
Qatif Bloc Jewish settlers, even though they are a very small 
group. The minister disclosed that the cost of the initial 
security arrangements will stand at approximately 30 million 
shekels, in addition to an annual outlay of 20 million shekels. 
As an example, he cited the need to build a security system, 
including a 7-km road to one of the settlements. "We are doing 
it to keep the agreement from collapsing," the minister noted. 
"The opponents of the agreement with the PLO are trying to 
scare and unnerve the residents of areas through which Arabs 
will drive," Peres said at a ceremony to mark the laying of the 
cornerstone for a new 'Amal technological college near Ashqelon. 
"It all depends on relationships, not security," the minister 
stressed. "There is no fence between Elat and al-'Aqabah, and 
relations there are excellent. Arabs live in Yafo, too. A new 
relationship must be created." 
  Peres denied rumors spread two days ago that Israel is not 
going to continue the talks with the PLO on the issues that 
remained unresolved when the Cairo agreement was signed. 
"Israel will adhere to its commitments," Peres stressed. With 
regard to foreign labor hired by Qatif farmers, the minister 
said it is preferable to employ Israeli laborers in agriculture. 

</TEXT>

