<F P=101> Yemen </F>
<H3> <TI>   Sanaa Under Curfew, Faces Fuel Shortages </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Sanaa Under Curfew, Faces Fuel Shortages </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   NC0805205294 Paris AFP in English 1946 GMT 8 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> NC0805205294 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Amman, May 8 (AFP) -- A nightly curfew has been 
imposed on the Yemeni capital Sanaa which is also facing severe 
fuel shortages, an evacuee who fled the city told AFP here. 
  The evacuee, who refused to be identified, said long queues 
form daily at petrol stations and the public transport system 
had been virtually brought to a standstill. 
  The curfew begins nightly at 9:00 p.m. until 5:00 a.m, after 
President 'Ali 'Abdallah Salih declared a state of emergency 
Thursday. 
  At night anti-aircraft salvos light up the sky searching out 
attacking southern planes, which have launched several air raids 
on the city, the Arab national said after landing on an 
evacuation flight in Jordan. 
  He added that a total news black-out had been imposed since 
fighting broke out four days ago between rival army forces, and 
amid reports that southern troops had fired Scud missiles at the 
capital. 
  He was not able to say whether there were any victims. 
  So far there has been no official casualty toll in the 
fighting which erupted Thursday, but an Islamic party supporting 
the president said Saturday 150 had died. 
  The evacuee was among 170 people, mainly UN personnel, flown 
out of Sanaa Sunday to Amman on a special flight. 
  Hundreds of foreigners have fled the war which has pitted 
Salih against his southern rival Vice President 'Ali Salim 
al-Bid. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

