<H3> <TI>   `Voice of Bosnia' Radio Inaugurated 10 May </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    `Voice of Bosnia' Radio Inaugurated 10 May </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Radio, TV Chief Comments </H4>

<F P=102> LD1005210794 Tehran Voice of the Islamic Republic of Iran 
First Program Network in Persian 1930 GMT 10 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1005210794 </F>
<F P=104>  Tehran Voice of the Islamic Republic of Iran 
First Program Network </F>

<F P=105>  Persian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The Voice of Bosnia started transmission via the 
Voice and Vision of the Islamic Republic of Iran during the 
final minutes of 9 May. 
  In an interview with our correspondent Pirhade'i about the 
reasons for starting the radio program and its effects on the 
course of events in Bosnia-Herzegovina, Mr. Larijani, the head 
of the Voice and Vision Organization of the Islamic Republic of 
Iran, said: 
  [Begin Larijani recording] In the name of God, the 
compassionate, the merciful. We are very glad that thanks to 
the efforts of the overseas department of the Voice and Vision 
and those involved in the project, the Bosnian program started, 
thank God. 
  Naturally, in the present world conditions, where in the 
heart of Europe there is an innocent nation whose situation is 
not understood by any of the superpowers -- you have seen in the 
news these days what they have done to the people of Gorazde. 
Transmitting the innocent call of those self-sacrificing and 
hardworking people was our religious duty. Because of the goal 
of the Islamic revolution in broadcasting the message of 
Muslims, it was a necessary task. We were able to make 
preparations quickly to start the program. 
  The program is transmitted at 2300 hours Tehran time [1930 
GMT] every night, on 9745 kHz, 31 m wave band, which is about 
2030 hours their time. We are trying to expand the program. We 
hope that we will quickly be able to make preparations to expand 
the program. 
  Of course, a great deal of effort went into the task, 
because 
they could not speak Persian well and had not received the 
necessary training. There were, naturally, problems for us in 
terms of translation. However, certain measures have been taken 
and I hope that the program will be expanded soon. 
  Undoubtedly such programs could have very favorable results 
in sending useful information to the people of Bosnia, 
considering the fact that they are under propaganda pressure, 
too. It is a small deed. By expanding the program, we are 
trying to transmit the information on time and at an appropriate 
volume to them. [end recording] 
  At the radio's inaugural ceremony, in addition to Voice and 
Vision officials, there were a number of officials of the 
Foreign Ministry, Ministry of Culture, and Islamic Guidance and 
a number of the radio's staff. 
  The programs of the radio, which will cover the Balkans, 
will 
include news on Bosnia-Herzegovina, commentary, report, 
developments in the world of Islam, and the culture and 
literature of Bosnia-Herzegovina. 

</TEXT>

