<F P=100> Iran </F>
<H3> <TI>   TEHRAN TIMES Notes U.S. Charges of `Supporting Terrorism' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    TEHRAN TIMES Notes U.S. Charges of `Supporting Terrorism' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1105090294 Tehran IRNA in English 0815 GMT 11 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1105090294 </F>
<F P=104>  Tehran IRNA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tehran, May 11, IRNA -- A morning English daily here 
Wednesday [11 May] said that Washington's charges against Iran 
and six other countries on supporting terrorist groups was only 
meant to divert world public opinion from its own activities. 
  Commenting on the publication of a report by the U.S. in 
which seven third world countries have been introduced as main 
supporters of terrorism, the `TEHRAN TIMES' wrote in its 
editorial that a brief look would reveal that all the seven 
countries were those that were not prepared to give in to the 
American global superpower role, and opposed Washington's 
expansionist policies. 
  The Central Intelligence Agency (CIA) was the greatest 
center 
for training terrorists, and coup d'etats and assassinations 
have been among the basic components of American foreign policy 
in the decades after World War II, argued the paper. 
  It concluded by saying that the relations between the 
American government and the terrorist groups was an "undeniable" 
fact. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

