<F P=100> ISRAEL </F>
<H3> <TI>   `Source:' No Discussion of Remaining PLO Demands </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    `Source:' No Discussion of Remaining PLO Demands </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   TA0805050794 Jerusalem Qol Yisra'el in Hebrew 0400 GMT 8 May 
94 </F>

<F P=103> TA0805050794 </F>
<F P=104>  Jerusalem Qol Yisra'el </F>
<F P=105>  Hebrew </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] A senior political source has told our political 
correspondent Shlomo Raz that Israel sees no point in discussing 
the issues that remain under contention with the PLO because it 
has no intention of acceding to the PLO's demands. 
  The disagreements revolve around the stationing of a 
Palestinian policeman on the Allenby Bridge, a Palestinian 
director at the Rafah border checkpoint, and the size of the 
Jericho enclave. U.S. Secretary of State Warren Christopher has 
been informed of Israel's position. 
  On 10 May, the working groups on refugee affairs will resume 
discussions in Cairo. The parties will stress the improvement 
of the refugees's living conditions and refrain from dealing 
with other aspects of the problem. 

</TEXT>

