<F P=100> JORDAN </F>
<H3> <TI>   `Sources' Cited on Nationals in Iraqi Jails </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    `Sources' Cited on Nationals in Iraqi Jails </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   JN0705153894 Kuwait AL-QABAS in Arabic 28 Apr 94 p 1 </F>
<F P=103> JN0705153894 </F>
<F P=104>  Kuwait AL-QABAS </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Amman--Well-informed Jordanian sources say that the 
Jordanian Deputy Prime Minister Sa'id al-Tall's recent visit to 
Baghdad dealt with the issue of Jordanian nationals being held 
in the Baghdad regime's jails. Official Jordanian circles 
estimate the number of these convicted detainees, who were 
charged with offenses ranging from illegal currency exchanges 
and smuggling to espionage for a foreign state, at 200. 
  The Jordanian Government is trying to solve this problem by 
reaching an understanding with the Iraqi authorities. 
  The sources also say that during his visit to Baghdad, 
al-Tall reached an agreement with the Iraqi officials on 
organizing a meeting between the interior ministers of the two 
countries in order to tackle unsolved issues facing the 
Jordanian nationals in Iraqi jails. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-59280 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drnes092_m_94008" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-NES-94-092 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  12 May 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> JORDAN </F>
<H3> <TI>   U.S. Embassy Said Extracting Info From Visa Applicants </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    U.S. Embassy Said Extracting Info From Visa Applicants </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   JN1205092494 Amman AKHBAR AL-USBU' in Arabic 12 May 94 pp 1, 
22 </F>

<F P=103> JN1205092494 </F>
<F P=104>  Amman AKHBAR AL-USBU' </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> ["Exclusive" report: "Tough Conditions Set by the U.S. </F>
Embassy To Extort Jordanians and Recruit Them Into Its 
Intelligence; the U.S. Embassy Offers Incentives To Hunt Iraqis 
and Obtain Information About Iraq"] 
  [Text] Amman -- The U.S. Embassy in Amman has provided many 
incentives to attract Iraqis wishing to emigrate to the United 
States. It set aside a special place for daily meetings at the 
embassy and appointed an intelligence team that tells the 
queuing petitioners every morning that "any Iraqi with important 
information to declare should step forward?!" 
  Eyewitnesses said three Iraqi women stepped out of a queue 
of 
150 persons when they heard the question and were immediately 
taken into the embassy. That day only these three women were 
granted visas while all other applications were rejected. 
  An applicant said the U.S. Embassy introduced two surprising 
articles and questions into the amended visa application forms. 
These are: Do you have important information [to declare], and 
do you know anything about underground and terrorist 
organizations and their places? Applicants say Palestinians, 
too, might be asked these questions. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

