<F P=100> SOUTH ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Iran </F>
<H3> <TI>   Rowhani Receives Canadian Envoy, Denounces 'Arafat </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Rowhani Receives Canadian Envoy, Denounces 'Arafat </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1005154694 Tehran IRNA in English 1501 GMT 10 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1005154694 </F>
<F P=104>  Tehran IRNA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tehran, May 10, IRNA -- Majles Vice-Speaker Hojjat 
ol-Eslam Hasan Rowhani said on Tuesday that inking any peace 
accord without the consent of the Palestinian people was a "big 
insult" to that nation. 
  "A real peace can be established only through Israel's 
unconditional compliance with U.N. resolutions, return of 
Palestinian refugees to their homeland and holding of a 
referendum," Rowhani told Canadian Ambassador to Iran Donald 
McLennan. 
  Rowhani, who is the secretary of the Supreme National 
Security Council (SNSC) reiterated that Palestine was not 
confined to a single person and that it was the Palestinian 
nation that should give final approval to such an important 
issue as peace. 
  "We have time and again expressed our views on the 
Palestinian issue...we have never decided, nor will we ever 
decide, to take a military action in the region," he said. 
  The Iranian parliamentarian maintained that it is only the 
Palestinian people, and no one else, who can make decision on 
the fate of Palestine. "What has been signed by (Palestine 
Liberation Organization Chairman Yasir) 'Arafat is an insult to 
the Palestinian people," he said. He felt confident that the 
Palestinian people will one day seize power as the majority 
black people of South Africa did. 
  The Majles vice speaker also criticized the United Nations 
for its failure to fulfil its duties in Bosnia-Herzegovina in 
defiance of its charter. 
  He said that in view of the sensitivity of the Persian Gulf 
region as a key energy supply center, Iran's strong presence in 
the region has always guaranteed security of the region and will 
continue to do so in the future. 
  Pointing to the importance of parliamentary relations 
between 
Iran and Canada, Rowhani called for exchange of delegations 
between the parliaments two countries. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

