<F P=101> United Arab Emirates </F>
<H3> <TI>   President Briefed on Events During Call From Yemen's al-Bid </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    President Briefed on Events During Call From Yemen's al-Bid </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   JN1105111294 Abu Dhabi United Arab Emirates Radio Network in 
Arabic 0930 GMT 11 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> JN1105111294 </F>
<F P=104>  Abu Dhabi United Arab Emirates Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] A responsible source has said that His Highness 
Shaykh Zayid Bin-Sultan Al Nuhayyan, the president, continues to 
follow with concern the developments in Yemen and that his 
highness is holding continuous sincere contacts and exerting 
genuine intensified efforts concerning the Yemeni crisis with 
his brothers the Arab leaders, urging Yemeni officials to 
immediately stop fighting, exercise self-restraint, and avoid 
more bloodshed among the sons of the one country. 
  The source added that his highness the president last night 
received a telephone call from 'Ali Salim al-Bid, vice president 
of the Yemeni Republic, during which he explained to his 
highness the latest developments in Yemen. 
  During the telephone conversation, His Highness Shaykh Zayid 
Bin-Sultan Al Nuhayyan expressed the United Arab Emirates' 
willingness to continue its mediation to restore stability in 
Yemen on condition there is an immediate cease-fire and a return 
to true brotherly dialogue in order to reach a political 
solution to the Yemeni crisis based on the vision of the Yemeni 
leadership. 
  The responsible source added that his highness the 
president's appeal to the leaders of Yemen truly reflects his 
highness's concern to prevent the situation in Yemen from 
becoming a tragedy with dire results and to prepare the 
atmosphere for dialogue and understanding among the brothers in 
Yemen. The appeal also reflects his highness's concern that the 
brothers in Yemen should fully shoulder their national 
responsibilities, not widen their differences, and to put the 
interest of the Yemeni people above all interests because 
history does not (?forgive). 

</TEXT>

