<F P=100> ARABIAN PENINSULA </F>
<F P=101> Yemen </F>
<H3> <TI>   3 Northern Warplanes Shot Down </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    3 Northern Warplanes Shot Down </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AB1205100094 Paris AFP in English 0938 GMT 12 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> AB1205100094 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Aden, Yemen, May 12 (AFP) -- Southern forces in 
Yemen's civil war shot down three northern warplanes and sank a 
warship west of the vital port city of Aden, a southern 
commander announced Thursday [12 May]. 
  Colonel 'Ali Qasim Taleb, the sacked Yemeni Navy chief, told 
the Aden daily OCTOBER 14 the northern targets were hit late 
Wednesday in the Kharaz region, near the strategic Bab el-Mandeb 
Straits on the Red Sea. 
  Earlier the northern forces loyal to President 'Ali 
'Abdallah 
Salih claimed they had captured a southern mechanised brigade 
based at Kharaz. 
  A northern military communique quoted by the official news 
agency SABA said northern forces had captured all the tanks and 
artillery of the southern 25th Mechanised Brigade, and many of 
the brigade's 1,200 soldiers had surrendered. 
  Southern leaders told AFP Wednesday that the north was 
attempting to open up a new front in the Bab al-Mandeb Straits 
area. 
  Both sides appeared to be heading for a stalemate along the 
pre-unification border formerly dividing conservative North 
Yemen and the Marxist south. 
  Salih's southern rival 'Ali Salim al-Bid, sacked by the 
northern-dominated parliament last week, said a ceasefire 
depended on the withdrawal of northern forces from the south. 
  "The return of forces to their positions (before unification 
in May 1990) is an important condition for ending the fighting," 
al-Bid told reporters at his home overlooking Aden. 
  A simmering feud between Salih and al-Bid over political and 
economic reforms boiled over into all-out war a week ago. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-59328 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drnes092_j_94024" </HT>


