<F P=100> ARABIAN PENINSULA </F>
<F P=101> Yemen </F>
<H3> <TI>   Electricity Official Comments on Repair of Damaged Station </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Electricity Official Comments on Repair of Damaged Station </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   JN1105113594 Sanaa Yemeni Republic Radio Network in Arabic 
0625 GMT 11 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> JN1105113594 </F>
<F P=104>  Sanaa Yemeni Republic Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Telephone interview with engineer 'Abd-al-Mu'ti al-Junayd, </F>
deputy director of projects in the General Electricity 
Corporation, by 'Abd-al-Malik al-'Ayzari in the studio -- live 
or recorded] 
  [Excerpt] [Al-Junayd] I am happy to explain to the brother 
citizens what happened to the electricity grid in the Dhamar 
area as a result of raids and shelling by the secessionists in 
the Ba Suhayb military camp. In fact, we are lucky because the 
damage was very limited, concentrating on electricity lines that 
extend from the station to feed the capital, Sanaa. 
  [Al-'Ayzari] This means the [words indistinct] lines? 
  [Al-Junayd] [Words indistinct] In the station itself, the 
damage is very minor and concentrated on the lines, [word 
indistinct] the lines extending from the Dhamar station to the 
capital, Sanaa. The brothers [words indistinct] took a position 
in favor of the constitutional legitimacy. Teams moved and the 
brothers from the General Electricity Corporation, with their 
equipment came and they defined the damage and began repair work. 
  The lines extend from the Dhamar transformers to Sanaa 
through two circuits. The teams in the area repaired the first 
circuit. A great effort was made and they were able to restore 
electric current to Sanaa. The day before yesterday at 8 or 9 
o'clock [am, pm not specified] they completed their task 
successfully, restoring power to Sanaa in a very normal way. 
  Repair work on the second circuit, which is really a reserve 
circuit, continues. It was hit harder. The brothers at the 
site [words indistinct] brother Ahmad al-'Ayni also present to 
have a firsthand knowledge of the situation. The repairs will 
be carried out and today, and tomorrow they will be able to 
repair everything and the electric power would be completely 
restored. 
  We tell the citizens that the electric current is available 
in the capital and there are no problems and their will be no 
cuts, God willing. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

